const Q_GOVERNMENT_1998=[{"id": "objective>Government>1998>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following defines the concept of government ?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the process of administering justice in a country</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the process of supervising the activities of the legislature</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the orderly management and control of the affairs of a country</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the orderly transfer of power to duly elected policticians</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Government is defined as the system or group of people governing an organized community, often a state. In the case of its broad associative definition, government normally consists of legislature, executive, and judiciary. It is the means by which state policy is enforced, as well as the mechanism for determining the policy of the state. Therefore, the correct answer is 'the orderly management and control of the affairs of a country'.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF GOVERNMENT : SOCIETY, STATE, NATION AND NATION-STATE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The most distinguishing characteristic of the state is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">population</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">territory</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> sovereighty</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The most distinguishing characteristic of a state is sovereignty. Sovereignty is the full right and power of a governing body over itself, without any interference from outside sources or bodies. In political theory, sovereignty is a substantive term designating supreme legitimate authority over some polity. Therefore, the correct answer is 'sovereignty'.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF GOVERNMENT : POWER, AUTHORITY, LEGITIMACY AND SOVEREIGNTY"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The judiciary assigns clear meaning to the laws by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> interpretation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enforcement</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adjudication</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">revision</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The judiciary assigns clear meaning to the laws by interpretation. This is because the judiciary's role is to interpret the laws and ensure they are applied correctly. Interpretation involves understanding the intent of the law and applying it to individual cases. This is different from enforcement, which is the role of the executive branch, and adjudication, which is the process of resolving disputes. Revision of laws is typically the role of the legislative branch.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : JUDICIARY FUNCTIONS, POWERS AND COMPONENTS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The structure of government implies the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">law making process of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">law enforcement process of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">organization of powers and functions of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">method of revenue allocation by government</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The structure of government implies the organization of powers and functions of government. This refers to how a government is organized, including the division of powers among different branches or levels of government, and the specific roles and responsibilities of each. The law making and enforcement processes are part of the functions of government, but they do not define its structure. The method of revenue allocation is also a function of government, but it does not define its structure.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF GOVERNMENT : STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If the central government has less powers than the component units, the constitution is said to be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">federal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unitary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">confederal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unwritten</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a confederal system of government, the central government has less power than the component units. This is because the component units (states or provinces) have sovereignty over their territories and they voluntarily join the confederation. They can also decide to leave the confederation at any time. This is different from a federal system where the central government and the component units share powers, and a unitary system where the central government has all the powers.</div>", "topic": "CONSTITUTION : TYPES OF CONSTITUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a democracy, ultimate authority resides in the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Electorate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">People</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Head of state</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">armed forces</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a democracy, the ultimate authority resides in the people. This is because democracy is a system of government where the citizens exercise power directly or elect representatives from among themselves to form a governing body. The concept of democracy is often summarized with the phrase 'government of the people, by the people, for the people'. Therefore, the people are the ultimate authority in a democracy.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF GOVERNMENT : POWER, AUTHORITY, LEGITIMACY AND SOVEREIGNTY"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A major characteristic of the socialist system is its provision for</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">limited privacy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">public ownership</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unlimited privacy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">private ownership</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Socialism is a populist economic and political system based on collective, common, or public ownership of the means of production. </div>", "topic": "POLITICAL IDEOLOGIES : SOCIALISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the presidential system of government, the chief executive is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elected by the entire electorate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nominated by the legislators</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">selected by the party with the majority of seats in the legislature</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">appointed by an independent judiciary</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the presidential system of government, the chief executive is elected by the entire electorate. This is a key feature of the presidential system, where the president is both the head of state and the head of government, and is directly elected by the people. Therefore, the correct answer is 'elected by the entire electorate'.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : EXECUTIVE-TYPES, FUNCTIONS AND POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The resignation of the cabinet after a defeat in parliament, is an expression of the principle of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">political accountability</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">collective responsibility</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">checks and balances</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rule of law</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The principle of collective responsibility is expressed when the cabinet resigns after a defeat in parliament. This principle means that all members of the cabinet are collectively responsible for the decisions made by the government. If the government suffers a defeat, all members of the cabinet are expected to resign, regardless of their personal involvement in the decision that led to the defeat.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : EXECUTIVE-TYPES, FUNCTIONS AND POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ceremonial and executive powers are fused in the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">parliamentary system of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">presidential system of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">federal system of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unitary system of government</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a presidential system of government, the president holds both ceremonial and executive powers. The president is the head of state, which is a ceremonial role, and the head of government, which is an executive role. This means that the president is responsible for executing laws and running the government, as well as performing ceremonial duties such as representing the country at official functions.</div>", "topic": "SYSTEMS OF GOVERNANCE : PARLIAMENTARY SYSTEM OF GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The rights of a citizen can be withdrawn by the state if the person</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">leaves the country</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is convicted by a court</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">opposes the government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is pronounced dead</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The rights of a citizen can be withdrawn by the state if the person is convicted by a court. This is because when a person is convicted of a crime, they may lose certain civil rights such as the right to vote, serve on a jury, or hold public office. The other options do not necessarily result in the loss of a citizen's rights.</div>", "topic": "CITIZENSHIP : CITIZENSHIP RIGHTS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The principle by which both the governors and the governed are bound by the laws is called</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">constitutionalism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">constitutional supremacy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rule by decree</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rule of law</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The principle by which both the governors and the governed are bound by the laws is called the rule of law. This principle means that no one is above the law and everyone must obey the law. Constitutionalism refers to the adherence to a system of constitutional government. Constitutional supremacy means that the constitution is the supreme law of the land and any law that is inconsistent with it is void. Rule by decree is a style of governance allowing quick, unchallenged creation of law by a single person or group, and is used primarily by dictators, absolute monarchs, and military leaders.</div>", "topic": "PRINCIPLES OF DEMOCRATIC GOVERNMENT : CONSTITUTIONALISM, RULE OF LAW AND REPRESENTATIVE GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The empowerment of the police service commission to make rules for the appointment, promotion and dismissal of its personnel, is an example of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> a decree</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a penal law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a delegated legislature</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an executive order</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The empowerment of the Police Service Commission to make rules for the appointment, promotion, and dismissal of its personnel is an example of a delegated legislature. Delegated legislation refers to the power given to an individual or body by a higher authority to make laws. In this case, the Police Service Commission has been given the power by a higher authority to make rules concerning its personnel.</div>", "topic": "PROCESSES OF LEGISLATION : DELEGATED LEGISLATION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In democracy, Franchise is given to all</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Adult citizens</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">citizens</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loyal party members</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resident adults</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a democracy, franchise is given to all adult citizens. Franchise refers to the right to vote in public elections. In a democratic system, this right is typically extended to all adult citizens, regardless of gender, race, or social status. This is a fundamental principle of democracy, ensuring that all citizens have a say in the governance of their country.</div>", "topic": "PRINCIPLES OF DEMOCRATIC GOVERNMENT : SEPARATION OF POWER, CHECKS AND BALANCES AND INDIVIDUAL/COLLECTIVE RESPONSIBILITY"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The major advantage of secret balloting is that it</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> allows people to vote freely</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ensures the anonymity of the voter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">extends the franchise to all adults</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is faster than the other systems</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The major advantage of secret balloting is that it ensures the anonymity of the voter. Secret balloting is a voting method in which a voter's choices in an election or a referendum are anonymous, forestalling attempts to influence the voter by intimidation, blackmailing, and potential vote buying. This system is one method of achieving the goal of political privacy.</div>", "topic": "ELECTIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A candidate who wins election by a simple majority, must have been voted for by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a majority of the electorate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">most of the electorate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a good number of the voters</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a majority of the voters</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A candidate who wins an election by a simple majority must have been voted for by a majority of the voters. A simple majority in the context of an election means the candidate with the most votes wins, regardless of whether that candidate has more than half the total votes. Therefore, the candidate must have been voted for by a majority of the voters, not necessarily a majority of the electorate or most of the electorate.</div>", "topic": "ELECTIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A party system can be defined by the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">structures of political parties</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">manner the government and the parties operate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">relationship between the parties and the voters</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">number of political parties in a country</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This is the correct option. The question is self explanatory in relation to the answer. <br/> </div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY SYSTEMS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One major aim of a pressure group is to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">capture political power</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">influence the polices of the government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">install a government of its choice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> implement policies that will benefit its members</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The major aim of a pressure group is to influence the policies of the government. Pressure groups are organized groups of people who come together with a common interest or goal, and they seek to influence public policy and decision-making processes. They do not seek to capture political power or install a government of their choice, but rather to influence the decisions made by those in power.</div>", "topic": "PRESSURE GROUPS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One effective way by which governments ascertain public support and reactions through</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the press</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">social mobilization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">opinion leaders</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elections</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This is the correct option. The question is self explanatory in relation to the answer. <br/> </div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF GOVERNMENT : POLITICAL PROCESSES: POLITICAL SOCIALIZATION, POLITICAL PARTICIPATION AND POLITICAL CULTURE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An acephalous, pre - colonial political system is best represented by the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Oyo empire</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Igbo political organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ijo polictical organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Benin empire</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An acephalous, pre-colonial political system is best represented by the Igbo political organization. Acephalous refers to a society which lacks political leaders or hierarchies. Such societies are also known as egalitarian or non-stratified societies. The Igbo political organization before the colonial era was largely acephalous, with decisions made by a general assembly of all adult males and some females.</div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS : OTHER PRE-COLONIAL SYSTEMS IN NIGERIA"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The administration of the capital of the emirate under the pre-colonial Hausa Fulani political system was entrusted to the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">galadima</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">waziri</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sarkin fada</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sarkin pawa</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Waziri is the administrator of the capital. The question is self explanatory in relation to the answer.</div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS : HAUSA PRE-COLONIAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Aro system in Igboland was a</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">political organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">commercial organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">religious organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> imperial organization</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Aro system in Igboland was a commercial organization. The Aro Confederacy, which existed in the region that is now Nigeria, was a trading and religious consortium of Igbo communities, controlled by the Aro people. The Aro were known for their influence in the region, largely due to their economic and religious powers.</div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS : IGBO PRE-COLONIAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1879, four British companies were merged to form the United African Company by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Frederick Lugard</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">John Beecroft</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tubman Goldie</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macgregor Laird</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The United African Company was formed by Tubman Goldie in 1879. He merged four British companies to form this company. The United African Company played a significant role in the colonization of Nigeria by the British.</div>", "topic": "IMPERIALIST PENETRATION : THE BRITISH PROCESS OF ACQUISITION – TRADE, MISSIONARY ACTIVITIES, COMPANY RULE, CROWN COLONY, PROTECTORATE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following was a feature of the government of a British protectorate</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Legislature Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Provincial Authority</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Executive Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Native Authority</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A feature of the government of a British protectorate was the Native Authority. The British colonial administration established the Native Authority system in their colonies, including protectorates, to govern the local population. The Native Authority was a system of indirect rule that used traditional rulers and institutions to govern the local population.</div>", "topic": "IMPERIALIST PENETRATION : THE BRITISH PROCESS OF ACQUISITION – TRADE, MISSIONARY ACTIVITIES, COMPANY RULE, CROWN COLONY, PROTECTORATE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Educated elite did not like the system of Indirect Rule in Nigeria because it</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not make provisions for them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was exploitative and cumbersome</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">made traditional ruiers too powerful</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was undemocratic and oppressive</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The system of Indirect Rule in Nigeria was not favored by the educated elite because it did not make provisions for them. Indirect Rule was a system of governance used by the British to control parts of their colonial empire, particularly in Africa and Asia, through pre-existing local power structures. These local power structures were usually traditional rulers. The educated elite were often left out of this system because they were not part of the traditional ruling class.</div>", "topic": "IMPERIALIST PENETRATION : THE BRITISH PROCESS OF ACQUISITION – TRADE, MISSIONARY ACTIVITIES, COMPANY RULE, CROWN COLONY, PROTECTORATE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Nigerian Council was created by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hugh Clifford</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Arthur Richards</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Frederick Lugard</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bernard Bourdillon</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Created in 1914 after almagamation. The question is self explanatory in relation to the answer.</div>", "topic": "CONSTITUTIONAL DEVELOPMENT IN NIGERIA : HUGH CLIFFORD CONSTITUTION 1922"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nationalism in Nigeria was facilitated by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the actions of the veterans of the two world wars and traditional rulers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the activities of Christian churches and missionaries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">education and urbanization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rapid economic growth</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nationalism in Nigeria was facilitated by education and urbanization. Education exposed Nigerians to the ideals of freedom and self-determination, while urbanization brought people from different ethnic groups together, fostering a sense of national identity. The other options, while they may have contributed in some way, were not the main facilitators of nationalism.</div>", "topic": "NATIONALISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 1946 constitution was remarkable because it</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">created ministerial positions in Nigeria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">introduced regional governments in Nigeria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">introduced for the first time, the elective principle</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">brought about self- government for Nigeria</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This is the correct option. The question is self explanatory in relation to the answer. <br/> </div>", "topic": "CONSTITUTIONAL DEVELOPMENT IN NIGERIA : ARTHUR RICHARDS CONSTITUTION 1946"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following statements is true about the 1963 and 1979 constitutions?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">both had provisions for the office of the president</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">both had provisions for the office of a constitutional president</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">both provided for the offices of prime minister and president</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">both had provisions for the office of an executive president</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 1963 and 1979 constitutions of Nigeria both had provisions for the office of the president. The 1963 constitution established Nigeria as a republic with Nnamdi Azikiwe as its first president, while the 1979 constitution, also known as the second republic constitution, provided for a presidential system of government with an executive president.</div>", "topic": "POST - INDEPENDENCE CONSTITUTIONS : 1963 CONSTITUTION CHARACTERISTICS AND SHORTCOMINGS~~POST - INDEPENDENCE CONSTITUTIONS : 1979 CONSTITUTION CHARACTERISTICS AND SHORTCOMINGS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The premier of Western Region immediately after independence was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Chief Obafemi Awolowo</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Chief Ladoke Akintola</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Dr. M.A Majekodunmi</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Alhaji D.S Adegbenro</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This is the correct option. The question is self explanatory in relation to the answer. <br/> </div>", "topic": "INSTITUTIONS OF GOVERNMENT IN THE POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : THE EXECUTIVE – STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS AND WORKINGS."}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the period 1960-1966, Nigeria was governed under the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">presidential system of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Westminster system of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Confederal system of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unitary system of government</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the period 1960-1966, Nigeria was governed under the Westminster system of government. The Westminster system is a democratic parliamentary system of government modeled after that of the United Kingdom system, embodying a series of procedures for operating a legislature. It is used, or was once used, in the national and subnational legislatures of most former British Empire colonies upon gaining responsible government, beginning with the first of the Canadian provinces in 1848 and the six Australian colonies between 1855 and 1890.</div>", "topic": "THE STRUCTURE AND WORKINGS OF NIGERIAN FEDERALISM : RATIONALE FOR A FEDERAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following was not established under the 1979 Nigerian constitution?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Economic Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Security Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Council on Education</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Defence Council</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The National Economic Council was not established under the 1979 Nigerian constitution. The National Economic Council (NEC) is one of the Federal Executive Bodies in Nigeria established by the provisions of Third Schedule, Part I, Section 153: Sub section (18 & 19) of the 1999 Constitution of the Federal Republic of Nigeria. It was not established under the 1979 constitution.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC COMMISSIONS ESTABLISHED BY THE 1979 AND SUBSEQUENT CONSTITUTIONS : THE CIVIL SERVICE COMMISSION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Federalism was adopted in Nigeria as a constitutional response to the problem of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">educational imbalance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">national identity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ethnic pluralism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">manpower and resources</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Federalism was adopted in Nigeria as a constitutional response to the problem of ethnic pluralism. Ethnic pluralism refers to the coexistence of multiple ethnic groups within a single society, each maintaining unique cultural identities. In Nigeria, there are over 250 ethnic groups, and federalism was seen as a way to ensure that no single group could dominate the others at the national level.</div>", "topic": "THE STRUCTURE AND WORKINGS OF NIGERIAN FEDERALISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a federal system, the power allocated to both the central and the state governments is said to be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exclusive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">concurrent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> residual</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inherent</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a federal system, the power allocated to both the central and the state governments is said to be concurrent. Concurrent powers are powers that are shared by both the state and the federal government. These powers may be exercised simultaneously within the same territory and in relation to the same body of citizens. They are distinguished from exclusive powers, which can only be exercised by one level of government.</div>", "topic": "THE STRUCTURE AND WORKINGS OF NIGERIAN FEDERALISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the botched Third Republic, the unit of representation in the House of Representative was the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">local government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">electoral ward</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">senatorial district</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">entire state</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the botched Third Republic of Nigeria, the unit of representation in the House of Representative was the electoral ward. This is because the electoral ward is the smallest unit of electoral administration, and it is from these wards that representatives are elected into the House of Representatives.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY POLITICS IN POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : THIRD REPUBLIC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Public corporations mainly differ from the ministries in that they</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are not bureaucratic</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">provide social services to the public</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">required highly professional staff</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are organization as business enterprises</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Public corporations mainly differ from the ministries in that they are organized as business enterprises. While both public corporations and ministries are part of the public sector, public corporations operate more like businesses, aiming to provide services efficiently and effectively, often charging for their services. Ministries, on the other hand, are part of the government's administrative structure and are not typically organized as business enterprises.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC CORPORATIONS AND PARASTATALS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The privatization of public corporation is aimed at</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">making their goods and services available</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">making them reliable</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">making them more efficient</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">allowing the public to control them</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The main aim of privatizing public corporations is to make them more efficient. Privatization is the process of transferring an enterprise or industry from the public sector to the private sector. The general expectation is that private companies will be more efficient due to the profit motive.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC CORPORATIONS AND PARASTATALS : DEREGULATION, PRIVATIZATION, COMMERCIALIZATION – OBJECTIVES, FEATURES, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One major democratic innovation in local government administration introduced by the Babangida regime was the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">appointment of portfolio councillors</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">appointment of retired military officers as sole administrators</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">selection of heads of personnel management departments from the councillors</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">separation of powers between the executive and legislative arms of the councils</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Babangida regime introduced the separation of powers between the executive and legislative arms of the councils in local government administration. This is a democratic innovation as it allows for checks and balances, preventing the abuse of power.</div>", "topic": "LOCAL GOVERNMENT :FEATURES OF LOCAL GOVERNMENT REFORMS 1976, 1989 - STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS, FINANCE AND INTER-GOVERNMENTAL RELATIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The change in the role of traditional rulers in local government administration in Nigeria can be attributed to the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1976 local government reforms</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">involvement of the military in politics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lack of support for the traditional rulers by the citizens</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1988 civil service reforms</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 1976 local government reforms in Nigeria significantly changed the role of traditional rulers in local government administration. Prior to the reforms, traditional rulers had significant administrative and judicial powers. However, the reforms reduced their powers and made them largely ceremonial. They were no longer involved in the day-to-day administration of local governments but were instead given advisory roles.</div>", "topic": "LOCAL GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following factors was not responsible for the military intervention in Nigerian politics in 1966?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Willingness of politicians to relinquish power</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Western Regional election of 1965</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The federal election of 1964</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ethnic politics and lawlessness</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The willingness of politicians to relinquish power was not a factor responsible for the military intervention in Nigerian politics in 1966. The military coup was largely a result of widespread corruption, the manipulation of census figures, the controversial federal election of 1964, the Western Regional election of 1965, and ethnic politics and lawlessness. The politicians were not willing to relinquish power, which was one of the reasons that led to the military intervention.</div>", "topic": "THE MILITARY IN NIGERIAN POLITICS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One outstanding action for which the GOWON administration will be remembered in Nigeria's political history is the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">organizatin of FESTAC</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">construction of roads</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">creation of twelve states</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">civil service purge</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Gowon administration will be remembered for the creation of twelve states in Nigeria. This was a significant event in Nigeria's political history as it was the first time the country was divided into states. This was done to address the issues of ethnic and regional imbalance that had plagued the country since independence. The creation of states was seen as a way to give more representation and autonomy to the various ethnic groups in the country.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : EXECUTIVE-TYPES, FUNCTIONS AND POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An example of Nigeria's external cultural relations is her</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">establishment of diplomatic relations with other nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">economic aid to neighbouring countries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exchange of students with friendly nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">trade interactions with developing countries</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria's external cultural relations can be seen in her exchange of students with friendly nations. This is a form of cultural diplomacy, which is a type of public diplomacy and soft power that includes the 'exchange of ideas, information, art, and other aspects of culture among nations and their peoples in order to foster mutual understanding'. The exchange of students allows for the sharing and understanding of each other's culture, traditions, and values.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : COMMONWEALTH"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The concept of Africa as the centre - piece of Nigerian foreign policy implies that Nigeria should</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">interfere in the internal affairs of other African states</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">support secessionist movements in Africa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">participate in any peace - keeping operation in Africa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lay more emphasis on African issues</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The concept of Africa as the centre-piece of Nigerian foreign policy implies that Nigeria should lay more emphasis on African issues. This is because the policy is aimed at promoting unity, peace, and cooperation among African countries. It does not necessarily mean interfering in the internal affairs of other African states or supporting secessionist movements. It also does not mean that Nigeria should participate in any peace-keeping operation in Africa, although this could be part of the policy if it is in line with promoting peace in Africa.</div>", "topic": "NIGERIA IN INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : THE AFRICAN UNION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The organ responsible for the general administration of ECOWAS is the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Executive Secretariat</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Council of Ministers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Authority of Heads of State and Government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tribunal of the Community</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The organ responsible for the general administration of ECOWAS (Economic Community of West African States) is the Executive Secretariat. The Executive Secretariat is responsible for implementing and executing the decisions of the other organs of ECOWAS. The Council of Ministers, Authority of Heads of State and Government, and Tribunal of the Community are other organs of ECOWAS, but they are not primarily responsible for its general administration.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : ECOWAS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The first international organization Nigeria joined after independence is the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">United Nations Organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">African Unity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Commonwealth of Nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">After gaining independence on October 1, 1960, Nigeria first joined the Commonwealth of Nations. The Commonwealth of Nations, generally known simply as the Commonwealth, is a political association of 54 member states, nearly all of which are former territories of the British Empire.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : UNO"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The headquarters of the Economic Commission for Africa is located in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ghana</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Kenya</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ethiopia</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The headquarters of the Economic Commission for Africa is located in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. The United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) is one of the UN's five regional commissions, with its mandate to promote the economic and social development of its member States, foster intra-regional integration, and promote international cooperation for Africa's development.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : ECONOMIC COMMISSION FOR AFRICA"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is the commonest means of expressing public opinion?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">handbill</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">newspaper</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">radio</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">television</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Public opinion is most commonly expressed through newspapers. Newspapers have a wide reach and are accessible to a large number of people. They provide a platform for individuals to express their views on various issues through letters to the editor, opinion pieces, and editorials. Newspapers also conduct polls and surveys to gauge public opinion on various issues.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC OPINION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Pre-colonial Yoruba system, the powers of the Oyomesi were checked by the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Baale</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ogboni</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Are Ona kankanfo</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bashorun</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the pre-colonial Yoruba system, the powers of the Oyomesi were checked by the Ogboni. The Ogboni was a powerful secret society made up of high-ranking individuals in the society. They served as a check on the powers of the Oyomesi and the Alaafin, ensuring that they did not abuse their powers. The Ogboni had the power to depose the Alaafin and could veto the decisions of the Oyomesi.</div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At independence in 1960, the permission to establish a diplomatic mission in Nigeria was not granted to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">USA</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Japan</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">UK</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">USSR</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At independence in 1960, Nigeria did not grant permission to the USSR to establish a diplomatic mission. This was due to the Cold War tensions and Nigeria's alignment with the Western bloc.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : UNO"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1998>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The security council of the United Nations Organization is composed of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Western Industrial nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the five permanent members</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the five permanent members and other members periodically elected</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eleven member states elected by the general assembly</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Five permanent members: China, France, Russian Federation, the United Kingdom, and the United States, and ten non-permanent members elected for two-year terms by the General Assembly (with end of term year)</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : UNO"}];
